If you tailor a generated file in such a way that certain imports are no longer required, and you remove those imports, each subsequent regen will bring them back. It sould be nice to have a way to block those imports from showing up.
We'll add support so that a pattern like this in the emf-merge.xml:
noImport="\s*//\s*no\s+import\s+([\w.*]*)\s*;\s*\n"
can be specified and will have the effect that any import comments matching that pattern will block the matching import from being merged, e.g., instead of deleting an import introduced by the generator, you can comment it out like this:
// no import org.eclipse.emf.ecore.provider.EcoreEditPlugin;
And then it won't come back.

I20040310

I often want to extract a loop body to its own method. If I have "continue"
statements in the loop body, the refactoring will not be allowed. Would
converting them to "return" statements be semantically preserving (if the entire
loop body is extracted, anyway)?

Exp:

<pre>
for (int i= 0; i < 10; i++) {
    if (condition1)
        continue;
    if (condition2)
        continue;

    doStuff();
}
</pre>

Extracting the loop body would produce:

<pre>
for (int i= 0; i < 10; i++) {
    loopBody();
}

// ...

private void loopBody() {
    if (condition1)
        return;
    if (condition2)
        return;

    doStuff();
}

</pre>

- set maximal line width to 80
- insert this main method:

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa = 0;
        int bbbbbbbbbbbbbbb = 0;
        int cccccccccccccccc = 0;
        int ddddddddddddd = 0;

        ddddddddddddd = aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa * bbbbbbbbbbbbbbb + cccccccccccccccc
                        * ddddddddddddd;
        ddddddddddddd = (aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa * bbbbbbbbbbbbbbb)
                        + (cccccccccccccccc * ddddddddddddd);
    }

- format the code (Ctrl-Shift-F)


The code formatter takes care about operator precedence defined by 
parantheses. It does not seem to care about the operator precedence defined by 
the language.

This should be optimized.

Here are few remarks (and more ?) about Thread Events model loader.

1/ I  think "Running" thread event at thread start time: I have added this in 
XMLthreadStartLoader.java (see patch file below).
2/ Same thing for "Dead" thread events when a thread ends: I have added this in 
XMLthreadEndLoader.java (see patch file below).
3/I have also changed all "setTime( time )" for the fourth XMLmon*.java file 
to "setTime(createDeltaTime())", seems to have better result in thread view
 (I prefer to see 10/20 s times rather than 1.079E9 seconds ! ;-) ).

